	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Aug 14th 5:49 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I died twice tonight because the cleric couldn't heal me. Why couldn't the cleric heal? Because she was nuking with smite. Yep, spending 70 mana for what, 100 damage? That 70 mana would go a long way to keeping the tanks alive long enough to deal damage. Maybe she would have had enough for one last heal if she hadn't jumped into the melee instead of medding after that. My rules for the future:<br><br>If I ever see a cleric nuking in an easy fight, I'm leaving the group.<br><br>If I ever see a cleric meleeing instead of meditating and healing during a hard fight, I'm turning and running for the zone.<br><br>A cleric in melee can speed up the easy fights. Good. I'm sure there are special cases where a cleric should nuke, but nothing except undead or finishing off a runner comes to mind. The point is that the primary job of a healer is to heal. And that means making sure the mana is there to heal, even if a wandering mob joins in.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
